 last strokes, while the mid-strokes descend less than half-way.",[206,207],{"type":41,"l":141,"from":43,"to":43,"h":142,"unit":45},{"type":47,"l":48,"from":43,"to":44,"h":144,"unit":45},{"_":209,"notBefore":210,"notAfter":211,"evidence":149,"precision":18},"The goods recovered from the tomb suggest a date in the 3rd century BCE",-300,-201,[213,214],{"_":55,"type":56,"ref":57},{"_":59,"type":60,"ref":61,"offset":62},[216],[65,66],[156,157],{"_":159,"role":160,"ref":161},{"_":220,"type":164},"ME23438",{"_":166,"mainLang":167,"languages":222},[166],{"n":80,"url":224,"height":171,"width":172,"desc":173,"surfaceType":85},"ISic004414_tiled.tif",[],[91,176,92,177],[97,179,98,180],[229,230,231,122,126,130,103,104,105,106,104,185,186,167],"isic004414","epitaph for eupolemos",{"_":120},"\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>Εὐπολέμου \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>",{"author":3,"date":4,"citedRange":234,"ptr":235,"ref":236,"title":2,"citation":5,"uri":6},"41 fig.23",{"target":191},{"_":115,"target":115},{"file":238,"uri":238,"title":239,"status":240,"editionAuthor":13,"type":241,"objectType":242,"material":246,"condition":36,"layoutDesc":247,"handNote":251,"date":256,"places":259,"geo":263,"provenance":55,"provenanceGeo":265,"country":70,"region":71,"settlement":59,"repository":266,"idno":270,"textLang":271,"tmNumber":36,"facsimile":273,"letterHeights":275,"publications":276,"zotero":277,"keywords":278,"html":283,"bibl":284},"ISic004415","Epitaph for Krimma, child of Aunakos",{"_":120},{"_":122,"ana":123,"ref":124},{"_":243,"ana":244,"ref":245},"plinth","#object.arch_element.plinth","https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/1910.html",{"_":130,"ana":131,"ref":132},{"layout":248},{"p":249,"rs":250,"damage":36},"Single line of greek letters approximately centred on the face of the plinth",{"_":33,"ana":34,"ref":35},{"lettering":252,"dimensions":253},"Small simple letters. Kappa has short equal arms, attached to the vertical; rho has small closed eye; mu has slanting first and final strokes, with the mid-strokes joining as a curve and only descending half-way; alpha is broad with straight bar, in one case slightly curved with the apex extending at the top; nu has shorter right vertical joining the diagonal above the line; omicron is small and mid-line.",[254,255],{"type":41,"l":141,"from":43,"to":43,"h":142,"unit":45},{"type":47,"l":48,"from":43,"to":44,"h":144,"unit":45},{"_":257,"notBefore":258,"notAfter":211,"evidence":149,"precision":18},"The tomb has not been excavated fully, but the cemetery went out of use around the end of the 3rd century BCE or early 2nd century, offering a terminus ante quem",-350,[260,262],{"_":55,"type":56,"ref":57,"corresp":261},"#findspot",{"_":59,"type":60,"ref":61,"offset":62},[264],[65,66],[156,157],{"_":267,"role":268,"ref":269},"Necropoli di Abakainon","site","http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/museum/186",{"type":164},{"_":166,"mainLang":167,"languages":272},[166],{"n":80,"url":274,"height":171,"width":172,"desc":173,"surfaceType":85},"ISic004415_tiled.tif",[],[91,177],[97,180],[279,280,281,122,243,130,103,104,105,106,104,282,186,167],"isic004415","epitaph for krimma, child of aunakos",{"_":120},"necropoli di abakainon","\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>Κριμμα Αυνακου \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>",{"author":3,"date":4,"citedRange":285,"ptr":286,"ref":287,"title":2,"citation":5,"uri":6},"28 fig.15 (and ref on p.113)",{"target":191},{"_":115,"target":115},{"file":289,"uri":289,"title":290,"status":291,"editionAuthor":13,"type":292,"objectType":293,"material":294,"condition":36,"layoutDesc":295,"handNote":299,"date":305,"places":306,"geo":309,"provenance":55,"provenanceGeo":311,"country":70,"region":71,"settlement":59,"repository":312,"idno":313,"textLang":314,"tmNumber":36,"facsimile":316,"letterHeights":318,"publications":319,"zotero":320,"keywords":321,"html":325,"bibl":326},"ISic004416","Epitaph for Philon, son Aunakos",{"_":120},{"_":122,"ana":123,"ref":124},{"_":243,"ana":244,"ref":245},{"_":130,"ana":131,"ref":132},{"layout":296},{"p":297,"rs":298,"damage":36},"Single line of greek letters approximately centred on the face of the plinth, descending to right",{"_":33,"ana":34,"ref":35},{"lettering":300,"dimensions":301},"Crude and irregularly carved large letters. Phi has a small eye, seemingly formed of two small loops; omega is small, mid-line, open, with outward/downward sloping tails; nu is large and uneven; alpha is broad, but the form of the bar is illegible; kappa has short equal arms joined to the vertical; omicron appears small and midline.",[302,304],{"type":41,"l":141,"from":43,"to":43,"h":303,"unit":45},"59",{"type":47,"l":48,"from":43,"to":44,"h":144,"unit":45},{"_":257,"notBefore":258,"notAfter":211,"evidence":149,"precision":18},[307,308],{"_":55,"type":56,"ref":57,"corresp":261},{"_":59,"type":60,"ref":61,"offset":62},[310],[65,66],[156,157],{"_":267,"role":268,"ref":269},{"type":164},{"_":166,"mainLang":167,"languages":315},[166],{"n":80,"url":317,"height":171,"width":172,"desc":173,"surfaceType":85},"ISic004416_tiled.tif",[],[91,177],[97,180],[322,323,324,122,243,130,103,104,105,106,104,282,186,167],"isic004416","epitaph for philon, son aunakos",{"_":120},"\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>Φίλων Αυ̣νακου \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>",{"author":3,"date":4,"citedRange":285,"ptr":327,"ref":328,"title":2,"citation":5,"uri":6},{"target":191},{"_":115,"target":115},{"file":330,"uri":330,"title":331,"status":332,"editionAuthor":13,"type":333,"objectType":334,"material":335,"condition":36,"layoutDesc":336,"handNote":340,"date":346,"places":347,"geo":350,"provenance":55,"provenanceGeo":352,"country":70,"region":71,"settlement":59,"repository":353,"idno":354,"textLang":355,"tmNumber":36,"facsimile":357,"letterHeights":359,"publications":360,"zotero":361,"keywords":362,"html":366,"bibl":367},"ISic004417","Epitaph for [-?-], child of Gerontios",{"_":120},{"_":122,"ana":123,"ref":124},{"_":243,"ana":244,"ref":245},{"_":130,"ana":131,"ref":132},{"layout":337},{"p":338,"rs":339,"damage":36},"Remains of two lines of Greek letters, apparently centred on the face of the plinth; the second line sits directly above the lower moulding",{"_":33,"ana":34,"ref":35},{"lettering":341,"dimensions":342},"Simple, widely spaced letters. Omega is wide and open, with horizontal tails; rho has a large, closed eye; omicron is small and mid-line; nu is regular and with both verticals full length",[343,345],{"type":41,"l":344,"from":43,"to":44,"h":142,"unit":45},"Line 1-2",{"type":47,"l":48,"from":43,"to":44,"unit":45},{"_":257,"notBefore":258,"notAfter":211,"evidence":149,"precision":18},[348,349],{"_":55,"type":56,"ref":57,"corresp":261},{"_":59,"type":60,"ref":61,"offset":62},[351],[65,66],[156,157],{"_":267,"role":268,"ref":269},{"type":164},{"_":166,"mainLang":167,"languages":356},[166],{"n":80,"url":358,"height":171,"width":172,"desc":173,"surfaceType":85},"ISic004417_tiled.tif",[],[91,92,177],[97,98,180],[363,364,365,122,243,130,103,104,105,106,104,282,186,167],"isic004417","epitaph for [-?-], child of gerontios",{"_":120},"\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]ω\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">.\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003Cbr id=\